repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
Two methods that Cython required were made private and no longer exported: `_PyInterpreterState_GetConfig` and `_PyUnicode_FastCopyCharacters` (the SHAs from CPython are in the commit messages).

This branch seem to work (I can compile ~the whole scientific python stack including numpy, scipy, pandas, and h5py), but I suspect that these are not the correct fixes.  

Please take this PR as a "bug report with patch".

comment_data.body: I think I'd rather just fall back to `PyUnicode_CopyCharacters` (which is the same thing but with some extra checks). The "expand the string in place if possible" is a significant optimization (for certain types of badly written code) so I'd rather not lose it entirely.
We generally try to avoid including internal CPython headers.
This can probably be done better with a `__Pyx_PyVectorcall_Function()` macro, in order to avoid doing this check wherever we use the function.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -2317,7 +2317,11 @@ static CYTHON_INLINE PyObject* __Pyx_PyObject_FastCallDict(PyObject *func, PyObj
     #endif
 
     #if CYTHON_VECTORCALL
+    #if PY_VERSION_HEX >= 0x030D0000
+    vectorcallfunc f = PyVectorcall_Function(func);
+    #else
     vectorcallfunc f = _PyVectorcall_Function(func);
+    #endif

comment_data.body: This is not needed any more, I missed removing this when I version-gated farther down in the code.
We may as well make the define 0x03080000 too and use the official name as far back as we can.

@@ -2317,7 +2317,11 @@ static CYTHON_INLINE PyObject* __Pyx_PyObject_FastCallDict(PyObject *func, PyObj
     #endif
 
     #if CYTHON_VECTORCALL
+    #if PY_VERSION_HEX >= 0x030D0000
+    vectorcallfunc f = PyVectorcall_Function(func);
+    #else
     vectorcallfunc f = _PyVectorcall_Function(func);
+    #endif
